Walls.

A wall is a solid barrier the player can't walk or pass through — the vertical counterpart to a platform's floor. Where a platform is ground you stand on, a wall is a block you bump into: walk into one and you're stopped at its face, with a bump sound to tell you it's there. Walls are built from a tile theme, carry their own health, and can be made destructible so the player (or a bomb, or a projectile) can smash through them, optionally leaving debris behind.

A wall is physical, audible construction. Its sibling, the blockage, is an invisible barrier that stops the player with a spoken message instead of a solid surface; see the blockages topic for when to reach for that instead.

How a wall works.

A wall fills a rectangular area and blocks every tile inside it. When the player walks into the wall they're stopped and a bump cue plays so they can feel the edge by ear; trying to jump up into a wall overhead halts the climb the same way. On 3d maps a wall is volumetric — it fills every height level between its minimum and maximum z, so it's a true floor-to-ceiling block rather than a single layer.

A wall carries health. When it's destroyable, weapons, bombs, and projectiles chip that health down, and once it reaches zero the wall plays its death cue and is removed — opening the path it was blocking. What it leaves behind depends on its destruction platform: nothing at all, an open gap, or a patch of debris (rubble, rocks, ash, and so on) left lying in the wall's footprint.

Walls and the scanning camera.

The transparent setting decides how the wall behaves toward the camera the player uses to scan the map from a distance. A normal, opaque wall stops the camera at its surface, just as it stops the player — the camera bumps and can't move past it. A transparent wall still announces itself as the camera crosses it, but lets the camera continue through to examine the area behind it. Either way the player on foot is physically blocked; transparency only affects whether the map can be scanned through the wall.

Wall fields.

The wall form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangular block. A wall always spans a range, even on 2d maps.

Health. How much damage the wall can absorb before it's destroyed, relevant only when destroyable is checked.

Wall sound. The tile theme the wall is built from, which supplies its bump, hurt, and death sounds. The default is the generic wall theme; other themes are chosen from the list.

Wall volume. How loud the wall's sounds play, from full down to silent.
Wall pitch. The pitch of the wall's sounds, as a percentage around one hundred.

Destruction platform. What's left in the wall's place when it's destroyed — none to leave nothing, air for an open gap the player can pass through, or a debris type (ash, branch, brokenglass, debris, fire, rocks, rubble, or woodpile) to drop a matching patch of rubble where the wall stood.

Destroyable (checkbox). When checked, the wall can be damaged and destroyed; when unchecked, it's a permanent barrier.
Transparent (checkbox). When checked, the scanning camera can pass through the wall to examine what's behind it; when unchecked, the camera is stopped at the wall's face. The player on foot is blocked either way.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the wall sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the bump clip of the highlighted theme, hold control and press L to hear its hurt clip, and hold control and press H to hear its death clip. You can also press a letter key to jump to the next wall theme starting with that letter.

Authoring walls by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a wall is: wall minx maxx miny maxy health walltype volume pitch destplat destroyable transparent. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: wall minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz health walltype volume pitch destplat destroyable transparent. Volume runs from zero down to minus one hundred and pitch is a percentage around one hundred. The destruction platform is the word none, air, or a debris type name. Destroyable and transparent are the literal words true or false, and the wall sound must match a wall theme folder name or the word wall.
